# while Loops

A `for` loop is ideal when you know the number of iterations in advance. A `while` loop is better when you repeat until something changes and you do not know how many iterations that will take.

```javascript
while (condition) {
    // runs as long as condition is true
}
```

The condition is checked **before** every iteration. If it is `false` from the start, the body never runs.

```javascript
let count = 1;
while (count <= 5) {
    console.log(count);
    count++;            // must change the condition eventually!
}
```

## Danger: the Infinite Loop

If you forget to update the variable that controls the condition, the loop runs forever:

```javascript
// DANGEROUS — count never changes
while (count <= 5) {
    console.log(count); // runs forever
}
```

Always ensure the loop body contains something that eventually makes the condition `false`.

## The do...while Loop

`do...while` is like `while` but checks the condition **after** the body runs. This guarantees the body runs at least once:

```javascript
let n = 10;
do {
    console.log(n);
    n++;
} while (n < 5);  // condition is already false, but body ran once
```

Use `do...while` when you need to run the body before deciding whether to repeat.

## break and continue

```javascript
for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    if (i === 3) continue;  // skip 3
    if (i === 7) break;     // stop at 7
    console.log(i);         // 0 1 2 4 5 6
}
```

- `break` — exits the loop immediately
- `continue` — skips the rest of the current iteration and moves to the next

Both work in `for`, `for...of`, and `while` loops.

In the code example below, you will see a `while` loop simulate a bank withdrawal session and `continue` skip invalid entries.

codeExample.code:
// Bank Withdrawal Session — while loop

let balance    = 5000;
const requests = [500, 1200, 3000, 200]; // predefined (no prompt())
let idx        = 0;

console.log(`Opening session. Balance: ₹${balance}`);

while (idx < requests.length && balance > 0) {
    const requested = requests[idx];
    idx++;

    if (requested <= 0) {
        console.log("Invalid amount — skipped.");
        continue;         // skip to next iteration
    }

    if (requested > balance) {
        console.log(`₹${requested} declined — insufficient funds.`);
        continue;
    }

    balance -= requested;
    console.log(`Withdrew ₹${requested} | Remaining: ₹${balance}`);

    if (balance === 0) {
        console.log("Balance zero. Session ending.");
        break;            // exit the loop early
    }
}

console.log(`\nSession closed. Final balance: ₹${balance}`);

